\begin_layout Subsection
Primary stress
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Primary stress falls on the first 
\emph on
heavy
\emph default
 syllable.
 A syllable is heavy iff it ends in a consonant or has a long vowel.
 If there are no heavy syllables, primary stress falls on the first syllable
 of the word.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Secondary stress
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In compound words, the first syllable of each constituent gets secondary
 stress.
 In all words, if the primary stress does not fall upon the first syllable,
 the first syllable gets secondary stress.
 For example, 
\series bold
pelerindin
\series default
 would be pronounced [ˌpɛlɛˈrindin].
 
\end_layout

