 agreement has developed.
 There is also a distinction between 
\emph on
light
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
dark
\emph default
 verbs, with slightly differing conjugation patterns; these descend from
 the front and back vowel harmony classes in proto-Sakasic.
 When adding multiple suffixes to a verb stem, noun-type lenition (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Noun-lenition"

\end_inset

) does 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 apply; however, there is a system of vowel syncope dependent on the light
 and dark conjugation classes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Light and dark conjugation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Identifying classification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ludhisyn verbs belong either to the 
\emph on
light conjugation
\emph default
 or the 
\emph on
dark conjugation
\emph default
.
 Identifying a verb's conjugation class is very easy; the citation form
 of a verb is the 3rd person, present tense form.
 Verbs ending in 
\series bold
-sta
\series default
 in the citation form belong to the light conjugation, and verbs ending
 in 
\series bold
-st
\series default
 belong to the dark conjugation.
 So for example, 
\series bold
kérista
\series default
 
\emph on
to love (a person)
\emph default
 is a light verb ,while 
\series bold
kumust
\series default
 
\emph on
to eat
\emph default
 is a dark verb.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One may wish to identify the conjugation class of a verb in running text,
 without access to its citation form --- in many conjugated forms the endings
 for the classes are identical.
 In this case, the first vowel of the word, in most cases, will indicate
 the class:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align center
